Here is an Arduino project to control two motors using the L298N motor driver:

```c
// Define motor pins
int motor1Pin1 = 5;
int motor1Pin2 = 6;
int motor2Pin1 = 7; 
int motor2Pin2 = 8;

// Define enable pins
int enable1 = 9;
int enable2 = 10;

void setup() {
  // Set all motor pins as outputs
  pinMode(motor1Pin1, OUTPUT);
  pinMode(motor1Pin2, OUTPUT);
  pinMode(motor2Pin1, OUTPUT);
  pinMode(motor2Pin2, OUTPUT);

  // Set enable pins as outputs
  pinMode(enable1, OUTPUT);
  pinMode(enable2, OUTPUT);

  // Enable motors
  digitalWrite(enable1, HIGH);
  digitalWrite(enable2, HIGH);
}

void loop() {
  // Motor 1 forward
  digitalWrite(motor1Pin1, HIGH);
  digitalWrite(motor1Pin2, LOW);

  // Motor 2 backward
  digitalWrite(motor2Pin1, LOW);
  digitalWrite(motor2Pin2, HIGH);
  delay(1000);

  // Motor 1 backward
  digitalWrite(motor1Pin1, LOW);
  digitalWrite(motor1Pin2, HIGH);

  // Motor 2 forward
  digitalWrite(motor2Pin1, HIGH);
  digitalWrite(motor2Pin2, LOW);
  delay(1000);

  // Stop motors
  digitalWrite(motor1Pin1, LOW);
  digitalWrite(motor1Pin2, LOW); 
  digitalWrite(motor2Pin1, LOW);
  digitalWrite(motor2Pin2, LOW);
  delay(1000);
}
```

This code will:

- Define pins for two motors and enable pins 
- Set all pins as outputs in the setup
- Enable the motors by setting the enable pins high
- In the loop, it will:
   - Run motor 1 forward and motor 2 backward for 1 sec
   - Run motor 1 backward and motor 2 forward for 1 sec
   - Stop all motors for 1 sec
   - Repeat

