Here's an example of asynchronous code in C using the libuv library:
```c
#include <uv.h>

void do_something(uv_work_t* req) {
    // Do some CPU-intensive work...
}

void after_work(uv_work_t* req, int status) {
    // Work is done!
    free(req);
}

int main() {
    uv_work_t* req = malloc(sizeof(uv_work_t));
    req->data = NULL;

    uv_queue_work(uv_default_loop(), req, do_something, after_work);

    uv_run(uv_default_loop(), UV_RUN_DEFAULT);

    free(req);
    return 0;
}
```

This code:

- Defines a `do_something()` function that will do some CPU-intensive asynchronous work
- Defines an `after_work()` callback that will be called when the work is done
- Creates a `uv_work_t` request and queues the work on the default libuv loop
- Runs the event loop with `uv_run()`
- The `do_something()` function will be called asynchronously, and the `after_work()` callback will be invoked when it completes
- This allows the main thread to remain responsive while the work is being done asynchronously 

So this is an example of performing asynchronous work in C using libuv. Let me know if you have any other questions!

